    "industrial_process_notes": "The most common industrial epoxy prepolymer, bisphenol A diglycidyl ether (BADGE/DGEBA), is made by reacting epichlorohydrin with bisphenol A. Pierre Castan is credited with discovering bisphenol-A-based epoxy resins in 1943 (building on Paul Schlack's 1934 work); Sylvan Greenlee patented a related formulation in 1946. Curing proceeds via exothermic crosslinking; hardener reactivity order (fastest to slowest) is thiols > aliphatic amines > cycloaliphatic amines > aromatic amines > anhydrides > phenols. Global epoxy resin market was valued at ~$8 billion in 2016.",
